  "diary": "What a perfect Sunday. Woke early with Miso purring on the bed, made tea by the window while the neighborhood was still quiet. The walk to Gas Works Park felt like a gift—that old industrial skeleton against the blue sky, ducks everywhere. I sat with my journal for almost an hour, just listening to the water lap against the shore. Stopped by the library after, picked up a mystery novel and caught up with Sarah at the desk. The grocery run was pleasant; Mr. Chen at the produce stand saved me the good salmon. Spent the afternoon in my favorite chair reading, Miso draped across my lap, soft music playing. Made a lovely dinner with herbs from the garden. By evening I felt that deep quiet that only a slow day can bring—the kind where you remember why you retired in the first place.",
  "thought_process": "The beautiful weather pulled me toward my usual Sunday rhythms, and I leaned into them completely. At sixty-seven, I've learned that structure matters, but so does permission to move slowly. I could have rushed through errands, but instead I let each task breathe—the park became a meditation, the library a social anchor, the kitchen a creative space. Miso's company throughout the day grounded everything. No major news or disruptions meant my mind stayed local, intimate. I think I chose leisure over productivity today because my body needed it, and because the season—early summer, golden light—reminded me that these quiet Sundays are the whole point of having retired.",
  "end_state": {
    "location": [
      -122.332,
      47.6605
    ],
    "energy": 35,
